\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uncorrelated and Homoskedastic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simplest estimator.
 This estimator assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $\SigmaB$
\end_inset

 is diagonal.
 The estimated covariance matrix is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Omega}=\hat{\SigmaB}\otimes(\bX'\bX)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\SigmaB}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon}_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 on the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ith
\end_layout

\end_inset

 diagonal and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bX$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $PK$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $PK+1$
\end_inset

 if a constant is included) matrix of regressors in the regular VAR case.
 To understand the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bX$
\end_inset

, decompose it as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bX=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bx_{1}\\
\bx_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\bx_{T}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the set of regressors in any of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 regression equations in a VAR.
 In the bivariate example above, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bx_{t}=[1\,\,\,y_{1,t-1}\,\,\,y_{2,t-1}\,\,\,y_{1,t-2}\,\,\,y_{2,t-2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bX$
\end_inset

 is motivated by noticing that a Pþorder VAR can be consistently estimated
 using OLS by regressing the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\by_{i}$
\end_inset

 vector on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bX$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\thetaB}_{i}=(\bX'\bX)^{-1}\bX'\by_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\thetaB}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of parameters in a VAR.
 In the bivariate VAR(2) above,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Omega}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\hat{\sigma}_{11}(\bX'\bX)^{-1} & \mathbf{0}_{MM}\\
\mathbf{0}_{MM} & \hat{\sigma}_{22}(\bX'\bX)^{-1}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{ii}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i,t}$
\end_inset

.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Correlated and Homoskedastic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlated homoskedastic case is similar to the previous case with the
 change that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\SigmaB}$
\end_inset

 is no longer assumed to be diagonal.
 Once this change has been made, the variance covariance estimator is identical
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Omega}=\hat{\SigmaB}\otimes(\bX'\bX)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the bivariate VAR(2) above,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Omega}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\hat{\sigma}_{11}(\bX'\bX)^{-1} & \hat{\sigma}_{12}(\bX'\bX)^{-1}\\
\hat{\sigma}_{21}(\bX'\bX)^{-1} & \hat{\sigma}_{22}(\bX'\bX)^{-1}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the estimated covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{j,t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{12}=\hat{\sigma}_{21}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uncorrelated and Heteroskedastic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When residuals are heteroskedastic a White (or sandwich) -style covariance
 estimator is required.
 The two parts of the sandwich are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bB}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bA}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\bA}=(\frac{\bX'\bX}{T})\otimes I_{K}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\bB}=T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilonB_{t}\epsilonB_{t}'\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once these two components have been computed, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\OmegaB}=T^{-1}\hat{\bA}^{-1}\hat{\bB}\hat{\bA}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption that the errors are uncorrelated in this form imposes that
 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{i,t}\epsilon_{j,t}\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'\convp\mathbf{0}_{MM}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bB}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

block diagonal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix where all of the elements in the off diagonal blocks are 0.
 In the bivariate VAR(2) above,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\bA}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{\bX'\bX}{T} & \mathbf{0}_{MM}\\
\mathbf{0}_{MM} & \frac{\bX'\bX}{T}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\bB}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{1,t}^{2}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}' & \mathbf{0}_{MM}\\
\mathbf{0}_{MM} & T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{2,t}^{2}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Finally the 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is present int he formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\OmegaB}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bA}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bB}$
\end_inset

 both converge to constants although the variance of the estimated coefficients
 should be decreasing with 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Correlated and Heteroskedastic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correlated heteroskedastic case is essentially identical to the uncorrelated
 heteroskedastic case where the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{i,t}\epsilon_{j,t}\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'\convp\mathbf{0}_{MM}$
\end_inset

 is not made.
 In the VAR(2) from above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bA}$
\end_inset

 is unchanged and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bB}$
\end_inset

 is now
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\bB}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{1,t}^{2}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}' & T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{1,t}\epsilon_{2,t}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'\\
T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{1,t}\epsilon_{2,t}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}' & T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\epsilon_{2,t}^{2}\otimes\bx_{t}\bx_{t}'
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the new value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bB}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\OmegaB}=T^{-1}\hat{\bA}^{-1}\hat{\bB}\hat{\bA}^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

